    <item>
      <title>Workflow: Deploying Node.js Apps with Kubernetes</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/k8s-pods/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 27 Oct 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/k8s-pods/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;prerequisites&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Prerequisites&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#prerequisites&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;To successfully follow and execute the App Deployment Workflow within a Kubernetes environment, you&amp;rsquo;ll need the following prerequisites:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;software-and-tools&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Software and Tools&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#software-and-tools&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Node.js&lt;/strong&gt;: Ensure Node.js is installed on your local development machine to set up and manage the Node.js application.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Docker&lt;/strong&gt;: Docker is essential for containerizing your application into a Docker image. Make sure Docker is installed and configured correctly to build and manage containerized applications.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Essential Docker Commands</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/docker-commands/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 08 Oct 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/docker-commands/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;display-docker-version-information&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Display Docker Version Information&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#display-docker-version-information&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;docker version&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This command provides information about the Docker Engine version.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;list-all-docker-images&#34;&gt;&#xA;  List All Docker Images&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#list-all-docker-images&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;docker images&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;This command lists all the Docker images available on your system.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h3 id=&#34;pull-an-image-from-the-registry&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Pull an Image from the Registry&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#pull-an-image-from-the-registry&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-shell&#34; data-lang=&#34;shell&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;docker pull &amp;lt;image_name&amp;gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;You can use this command to download a Docker image from a container registry, like Docker Hub.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Getting Started with Docker for Go</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/docker-go/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 21 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/docker-go/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-is-a-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;  What Is a Container?&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;heading-link&#34; href=&#34;#what-is-a-container&#34;&gt;&#xA;    &lt;i class=&#34;fa-solid fa-link&#34; aria-hidden=&#34;true&#34; title=&#34;Link to heading&#34;&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&#xA;    &lt;span class=&#34;sr-only&#34;&gt;Link to heading&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Containers are like isolating an application so it thinks it&amp;rsquo;s running all by itself. It&amp;rsquo;s similar to a virtual machine (VM) but uses the host&amp;rsquo;s operating system instead of its own. To start a container, you begin with a container image that bundles up everything the application needs to run, making it easy to share and distribute.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The isolation that tricks a container into believing it has control over a whole Linux machine is achieved through the use of namespaces and control groups.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
